<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12075k"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12075k">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12075k"> 75(k)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> massiers / croix du Fief / hart / fouet / all Jews &amp; pagans out from / Spy Wedns to E &mdash; W &mdash;</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">? l&apos;ancienne <mark>croix du Fief</mark>, qui disparut &agrave; la R&eacute;volution. La croix se dressait jadis, en dehors des murs et dans le port, sur un &icirc;lot de pierres brutes qui lui servait de pi&eacute;destal. Elle &eacute;tait l&apos;intersigne de la juridiction de la seigneurie commune de l&apos;Ev&ecirc;que et du Chapitre de Saint-Malo. C&apos;est au pied de cette croix, &ldquo;que tous les trois mois, les gens de la pr&eacute;v&ocirc;t&eacute; eccl&eacute;siastique venaient avertir, &agrave; son de trompe, apr&egrave;s le dernier coup de l&apos;Angelus de midi, tous les tenanciers en r&ocirc;ture de l&apos;&eacute;v&ecirc;que et du chapitre, d&apos;avoir &agrave; payer leurs redevances sous les trois jours, si mieux n&apos;aimaient voir leurs meubles vendus et leurs personnes emprisonn&eacute;es, pour encourir le bannissement, non seulement de la ville, mais aussi de tout le territoire relevant de la juridiction eccl&eacute;siastique" (E. Herpin). C&apos;est aussi &agrave; la croix du Fief que &ldquo;le Mercredi-Saint de chaque ann&eacute;e, le grand chanoine p&eacute;nitencier, accompagn&eacute; de son chapelain, de son enfant de choeur et de quatre <mark>massiers</mark>, se rendait, en habit de choeur, publier l&apos;ordonnance qui prescrivait &agrave; tous les Juifs et pa&iuml;ens, sous peine <mark>du hart et du fouet</mark>, de d&eacute;guerpir avant le premier son de l&apos;Angelus, avec d&eacute;fense de rentrer avant le mercredi de P&acirc;ques &agrave; midi&rdquo; (E. Herpin)] <br><font color="green">[? the ancient cross of the Fief, which disappeared during the Revolution. This cross used to stand, outside of the walls and in the port, in a little island of rough stones that served as a pedestal. It was a symbol of the jurisdiction of the common lordship of the Bishop and the Chapter of Saint-Malo. It was on the foot of this cross &ldquo;that every three months, people from the church&apos;s Provost came to warn, with the sound of trumpets after the last bell of the noon Angelus, all the tenants in the service of the bishop and the chapter, to pay their dues within three days, if they did not want to see their furniture sold and themselves in prison, to be banned from the city and also from all the land within the jurisdiction of the church&rdquo; (E. Herpin). It is also at the cross of the Fief that &ldquo;on Ash Wednesday of each year, the great penitentiary canon, accompanied by his chaplain, his choir boy and four mace-bearers, went, in choir dress, to proclaim the ordinance that <mark>ordered all jews and pagans, under pain of the rope and the whip, to leave before the first sound of the Angelus, and to come back before Easter at noon</mark>&rdquo; (E. Herpin)]</font> <small> Eug&egrave;ne Herpin, <a name="ADLS" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#ADLS"><cite title="source">La Croix du Fief</cite></a> (1911) 160</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
